---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { tools, verticals } from '../lib/data';

const lastUpdated = 'May 29, 2026';
const toolCount = tools.length;
const verticalCount = verticals.length;

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Editorial Standards', url: '/editorial-standards/' },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Editorial Standards & How We Research — WrenchStack"
  description="How WrenchStack researches, verifies, and publishes: our sourcing, fact-checking, independence, reputation-flag, and corrections standards. Vendor-funded, never vendor-influenced."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 prose prose-slate">
    <div class="not-prose mb-8">
      <p class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-orange-600">How we work</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl m-0">Editorial Standards</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-500">Last updated: {lastUpdated}</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      WrenchStack is an independent research publication covering the software and services that trades
      and field-service businesses buy. We are not a vendor, not a lead broker, and not for sale. These
      are the standards every page on this site is held to. If we ever fall short of them, email
      <a href="mailto:hello@wrenchstack.com">hello@wrenchstack.com</a> and we'll fix it.
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6 rounded-lg border-2 border-emerald-200 bg-emerald-50 p-5">
      <p class="m-0 text-sm leading-relaxed text-emerald-900">
        <strong>The one rule everything else serves:</strong> a vendor cannot pay us for a higher score,
        a better ranking, inclusion in a "best of" list, a softer review, or the removal of a reputation
        warning. We earn affiliate commissions on some sign-ups, and that never changes what we publish.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>How we research</h2>
    <p>
      Every vendor goes through the same documented process before it's published, regardless of whether
      we have a commercial relationship with it:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Identify.</strong> Vendors enter the directory through editorial research, category sweeps, contractor requests, or vendor submissions — never by paying for placement.</li>
      <li><strong>Collect from primary sources.</strong> Pricing comes from the vendor's own public pricing page; features from official documentation and product demos; integrations from official integration directories.</li>
      <li><strong>Aggregate third-party signal.</strong> We pull user ratings from G2 and Capterra and read sentiment across Reddit, BBB, Trustpilot, and trade forums.</li>
      <li><strong>Score consistently.</strong> Every vendor is rated with the same published <a href="/methodology/">WrenchStack Fit Score™</a> formula and weights.</li>
      <li><strong>Write and review.</strong> Each review is drafted, checked against the standards on this page, and published with a verification date.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      The full step-by-step timeline and the scoring weights are documented on our
      <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>, which is versioned and carries a public changelog.
    </p>

    <h2>How we verify</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pricing is dated.</strong> Every pricing figure carries a <em>verified date</em> and is re-checked quarterly. Anything older than 90 days is flagged for re-verification before it ranks.</li>
      <li><strong>Primary sources win.</strong> When a vendor's claim contradicts its own public page, we publish what the public page says until the page changes.</li>
      <li><strong>No fabricated signals.</strong> We do not invent review counts, ratings, or testimonials. Where we have no first-party reviews for a tool, we say so rather than manufacture them.</li>
      <li><strong>Custom-quoted pricing is labeled.</strong> For enterprise tools without public pricing, we cite user-reported ranges from public sources and mark them as such — never a number we made up.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Our sources</h2>
    <p>
      Primary sources are vendor pricing pages, official product documentation, and integration
      directories. Third-party sources include G2 and Capterra (ratings), and BBB, the FTC, Trustpilot,
      Reddit, and trade forums (reputation and sentiment). When we attach a reputation warning to a
      vendor, we cite the documented basis for it.
    </p>

    <h2>How reputation flags work</h2>
    <p>
      Some vendors carry a reputation warning. We apply these based on <strong>documented patterns</strong>
      — FTC settlements or actions, class-action history, high BBB complaint volume, or consistent
      customer-reported problems (for example, lead-quality complaints or aggressive lock-in contracts).
      A flag is applied on the evidence alone. We flag vendors we earn commissions from, and we recommend
      vendors we earn nothing from, when that's where the evidence points.
    </p>

    <h2>Independence and how we make money</h2>
    <p>
      WrenchStack is reader-focused and affiliate-funded: when you sign up with some vendors through our
      links, we may earn a commission, at no extra cost to you. That funding pays for the research; it
      does not influence it. The same Fit Score formula, the same reputation standards, and the same
      editorial scrutiny apply to every vendor — affiliate partner or not. See our
      <a href="/disclosure/">affiliate disclosure</a> and the per-vendor affiliate ledger on the
      <a href="/methodology/#affiliate-ledger">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If we get something wrong — a price, a feature, a claim — we correct it within 48 hours of
      confirmation, and the correction is noted on the page with a date. We never silently edit a
      substantive error away. Spotted one? Email
      <a href="mailto:hello@wrenchstack.com">hello@wrenchstack.com</a> with the page URL and what's wrong.
    </p>

    <h2>Who is accountable</h2>
    <p>
      WrenchStack operates as a research desk with defined editorial roles — Editor-in-Chief, Methodology
      Lead, Data Operations, and Vendor Relations — even where those roles consolidate in early
      operations. Every review is held to the standards on this page; vendor relationships are managed
      separately from editorial scoring. Editorial questions and accountability go to
      <a href="mailto:hello@wrenchstack.com">hello@wrenchstack.com</a>. Learn more
      <a href="/about/">about WrenchStack</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Keeping {toolCount}+ tools across {verticalCount} trades current</h2>
    <p>
      Coverage at this scale only stays useful if it stays fresh. We use data tooling and automation to
      track pricing and structure information across the directory, and a quarterly refresh cycle to
      re-verify pricing, re-pull ratings, and re-evaluate reputation flags. The standards on this page
      govern what gets published — the tooling helps us hold the line at scale, it doesn't replace the
      judgment.
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 text-sm text-slate-600">
      Related: <a href="/methodology/" class="font-medium text-slate-900 hover:underline">WrenchStack Fit Score™ Methodology</a>
      · <a href="/disclosure/" class="font-medium text-slate-900 hover:underline">Affiliate disclosure</a>
      · <a href="/about/" class="font-medium text-slate-900 hover:underline">About</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
